That's why I need to have exhibitions regularly - to finish a thinking process and to move on to a next phase. Then, in the context of an exhibition, something is “ready”. If I show it again later, I will have to review everything once again. The final decisions, just before a show, are also the most difficult for me.

questions.finished: when it doesn't call me no more to go on and change or risk a little more.. sometimes I want to trick myself, I feel tempted to tell myself, 'It's good, it's finished' but tricking yourself is not really working... you won't be convinced... so you have to go on... sometimes that ends in a destroyed work, but better to try to finish.. sometimes it's clear, it's finished and it's all good.. sometimes it's finished. I don't believe in 'happy ends', there may be some.. but alot of times you don't understand everything about a piece when it's finished.. You have the intuition that it might make sense later on.. A dear friend of mine, the wonderful painter Eva Bodnar, who was teaching nude drawing (Abendakt) at the Academy of fine Arts Vienna, she said, 'forget about Happy End, 'Happy Anfang' that is better...
